                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p39883d25/manifest/annotation/p1",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p rend=\"align(right)\">\n                                        <placeName>1 Presde Ville Place</placeName>\n                              </p>\n                              <p rend=\"align(right)\">\n                                        <placeName>Montreal</placeName>\n                              </p>\n                              <p rend=\"align(right)\">\n                                        <date>Nov 24 1847</date>\n                              </p>\n                              <p>\n                                        <addressee>Rev Isaac Leeser</addressee>\n                              </p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(1)\">\n                                        <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>\n                              </p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(2)\">My dear Friend</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(3)\">You flatter me much when you say<lb/> you will be\n                                        happy to count me among the few you favor with<lb/> an\n                                        interchange of communication. Though I am pleased to stand\n                                        in<lb/> correspondence with the <persName>Rev Isaac\n                                                  Leeser</persName> Minister of the\n                                                  <sic>Portugese</sic> Israelites<lb/> in\n                                                  <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> I am much more\n                                        pleased to communicate with the Editor<lb/> of the Occident,\n                                        and the author of the \"Jewish Discourses,\" and of the\n                                        \"Mosaic<lb/> Law\" If therefore I am at any time not to\n                                        remedy in answering your favors<lb/> as this feeling would\n                                        prompt, do not impute it to neglect but to its<lb/> true\n                                        cause inability. It has been inability that has prevented my\n                                        answering<lb/> yours of the <date>16th</date> till the\n                                        present moment, and it has been inability that<lb/> has\n                                        forbidden my sending you by opportunity of <persName>Mr\n                                                  Joseph</persName> an article which<lb/> I have but\n                                        just now been able to commence, and which I promised\n                                        you<lb/> in my last. I know not whether it will suit the\n                                        Occident, because<lb/> although a Jewish subject, it is\n                                        likely to prove more interesting to the readers<lb/> of a\n                                        British Periodical, it may be called an Essay or\n                                                  <sic>Enquiry</sic> into the first<lb/> settlement\n                                        of Jews in <placeName>England</placeName>. When in\n                                                  <placeName>London</placeName> I took some little\n                                        trouble<lb/> in collecting materials for the subject and in\n                                        the above form they<lb/> are much at the service of yourself\n                                        and of the readers of the Occident<lb/> Please let me know\n                                        by earliest opportunity whether you [?] to<lb/> receive it.\n                                        I would have sent you sermon for publication but<lb/>\n                                        suppose that even now you would be unable to insert it\n                                        from<lb/> the number you have on hand. Will my father's be\n                                        among those<lb/> you intend publishing. English news would\n                                        lead one to believe</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p39883d25/canvas/p1"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
